[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating exception handling**\n\nI'm working with the metadata for ConstructorBackedException and need to ensure existing resources aren't modified. If a new exception is added in a new file, it seems that the metadata needs to be generated externally, as Forge is meant to handle that. Yet, if tests run before the metadata generation and resources are from a prior agent, there could be issues. It looks acceptable to reuse ConstructorBackedException to make sure the current tests pass, even if we don’t run them. It's a complex situation!\n\n**Analyzing test requirements**\n\nCreating a new test using an existing exception won’t necessitate any metadata changes since it’s in the same package and accesses a public class. I think using tryCopyException with ConstructorBackedException will suffice because it's already cached in the old test. Even if the old test runs first, it invokes the cached constructor each time, ensuring coverage. But I wonder, since the current old test class name maps to the outer structure, does it affect instrumentation counts? Following the user's guidance, I’ll create a dedicated file solely for the active class to maintain proper coverage.\n\n**Evaluating outer class coverage**\n\nI'm considering the existing file for the outer class that handles getConstructors and getDeclaredFields, which also reaches the active call. I wonder if we can remove the part that interacts with the active call while still maintaining outer coverage. The current test file covers both aspects, but if I take that part out, could it negatively impact the outer coverage? I think new dedicated coverage is possible, but I'd need to check the style of other test files for guidance.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_09d8b5e4b3d86acf0169f98020ac0c819ca1cad22b2e1f42b8\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp-YApNGivHUGrJgSVMwvo38BcdVr6AhoLfrsoD