urce line 54 for proper coverage checks. However, the user wants me to focus on the active class, which is a different direction. It seems they expect only tests, not infrastructure details. \\n\\nI'm considering that the \\\"none\\\" response may indicate that our test didn't trigger. So, I think it’s a good idea to add a behavioral test using the public coroutine API to confirm this!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Testing JaCoCo configuration**\\n\\nI'm thinking about JaCoCo and how the XML report shows the `safeCtor$1` class with no methods after the existing tests. It's a filter that doesn't rely on execution, so direct invocation won't alter the report structure. Therefore, I conclude that it won't help. I'm considering whether we could adjust JaCoCo to include the option \\\"includeKotlinGeneratedClasses = true\\\" for better coverage reporting. Let's explore that idea further!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_sBRrP98KZo8ta7BLuqFXEq0A|fc_09d8b5e4b3d86acf0169f981d32c10819c9464ca1a5d2159cb", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "grep -R \"includeKotlin\" -n ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.jacoco* 2>/dev/null | head"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1869, "output": 1606, "cacheRead": 50176, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 53651, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777959354454, "responseId": "resp_09d8b5e4b3d86acf0169f981bb13e8819c91b68d2c94c2dbfa"}}
